ðŸ”¹ Steps to Load a CSV File in Python


1. Import pandas
import pandas as pd


2. Load the CSV
df = pd.read_csv("your_file.csv")

- Replace "your_file.csv" with the actual path to your file.
- If the file is in the same folder as your script, just the filename is enough.
- If itâ€™s elsewhere, provide the full path (e.g., "C:/Users/AVCOE/Documents/data.csv").

3. Inspect the Data
print(df.head())   # Shows first 5 rows
print(df.info())   # Summary of columns and data types
print(df.shape)    # Rows and columns count


ðŸ”¹ Common Options You Might Need
- Custom delimiter (like ; or \t):
df = pd.read_csv("your_file.csv", delimiter=";")
- Handle missing values:
df = pd.read_csv("your_file.csv", na_values=["NA", "missing"])
- Specify encoding (important for non-English text):
df = pd.read_csv("your_file.csv", encoding="utf-8")
- Load only specific columns:
df = pd.read_csv("your_file.csv", usecols=["Column1", "Column2"])


ðŸ”¹ Example with Advertising Data
Since youâ€™re working on advertising analytics, suppose your CSV has columns like:
Date, Campaign, Impressions, Clicks, Spend


You can load and quickly check performance metrics:
df = pd.read_csv("ads_data.csv")

# Calculate CTR (Click-Through Rate)
df["CTR"] = df["Clicks"] / df["Impressions"]

# Calculate CPC (Cost Per Click)
df["CPC"] = df["Spend"] / df["Clicks"]

print(df.head())




